WEBVTT

00:25.960 --> 00:27.360
CHAPTER XIV.

00:27.360 --> 00:32.720
The Hotel Concert

00:33.980 --> 00:40.440
Put on your white organdy, by all means, Anne, advised Diana decidedly.

00:40.840 --> 00:43.580
They were together in the east gable chamber.

00:44.420 --> 00:51.860
Outside it was only twilight, a lovely yellowish-green twilight, with a clear blue cloudless sky.

00:52.460 --> 01:01.000
A big round moon, slowly deepening from her pallid luster into burnished silver, hung over the haunted wood.

01:01.960 --> 01:11.620
The air was full of sweet summer sounds, sleepy birds twittering, freakish breezes, far-away voices and laughter.

01:12.460 --> 01:20.360
But in Anne's room the blind was drawn and the lamp lighted, for an important toilet was being made.

01:21.060 --> 01:27.020
The east gable was a very different place from what it had been on that night four years before,

01:27.520 --> 01:34.240
when Anne had felt its bareness penetrate to the marrow of her spirit with its inhospitable chill.

01:35.200 --> 01:44.960
Changes had crept in, Marilla conniving at them resignedly, until it was as sweet and dainty a nest as a young girl could desire.

01:45.600 --> 01:54.180
The velvet carpet with the pink roses and the pink silk curtains of Anne's early visions had certainly never materialized,

01:54.520 --> 02:00.160
but her dreams had kept pace with her growth, and it is not probable she lamented them.

02:01.000 --> 02:11.220
The floor was covered with a pretty matting, and the curtains that softened the high window and fluttered in the vagrant breezes were of pale green art muslin.

02:11.860 --> 02:23.840
The walls, hung not with gold and silver brocade tapestry, but with a dainty apple blossom paper, were adorned with a few good pictures given Anne by Mrs. Allen.

02:24.860 --> 02:34.140
Miss Stacy's photograph occupied the place of honor, and Anne made a sentimental point of keeping fresh flowers on the bracket under it.

02:34.780 --> 02:41.240
Tonight a spike of white lilies faintly perfumed the room like the dream of a fragrance.

02:42.000 --> 02:48.640
There was no mahogany furniture, but there was a white painted bookcase filled with books,

02:49.220 --> 02:54.440
a cushioned wicker rocker, a toilet table befrilled with white muslin,

02:54.980 --> 03:06.960
a quaint, gilt-framed mirror with chubby pink cupids and purple grapes painted over its archtop that used to hang in the spare room, and a low, white bed.

03:08.400 --> 03:11.780
Anne was dressing for a concert at the White Sands Hotel.

03:12.520 --> 03:22.760
The guests had got it up in aid of the Charlottetown Hospital, and had hunted out all the available amateur talent in the surrounding districts to help it along.

03:23.400 --> 03:30.640
Bertha Sampson and Pearl Clay of the White Sands Baptist Choir had been asked to sing a duet.

03:30.960 --> 03:34.460
Milton Clarke of Newbridge was to give a violin solo.

03:35.360 --> 03:39.640
Winnie Adella Blair of Carmody was to sing a Scotch ballad.

03:40.160 --> 03:46.260
And Laura Spencer of Spencervale and Anne Shirley of Avonlea were to recite.

03:47.300 --> 03:56.560
As Anne would have said at one time, it was an epoch in her life, and she was deliciously a thrill with the excitement of it.

03:57.260 --> 04:03.380
Matthew was in the seventh heaven of gratified pride over the honor conferred on his Anne,

04:03.820 --> 04:09.340
and Marilla was not far behind, although she would have died rather than admit it,

04:09.340 --> 04:18.680
and said she didn't think it was very proper for a lot of young folks to be gadding over to the hotel without any responsible person with them.

04:19.740 --> 04:26.240
Anne and Diana were to drive over with Jane Andrews and her brother Billy in their double-seated buggy,

04:26.560 --> 04:30.100
and several other Avonlea girls and boys were going too.

04:30.640 --> 04:38.480
There was a party of visitors expected out from town, and after the concert a supper was to be given to the performers.

04:39.420 --> 04:44.220
Do you really think the organdy will be best? queried Anne anxiously.

04:44.900 --> 04:50.060
I don't think it's as pretty as my blue-flowered muslin, and it certainly isn't so fashionable.

04:51.120 --> 04:54.540
But it suits you ever so much better, said Diana.

04:55.080 --> 04:57.600
It's so soft and frilly and clinging.

04:58.240 --> 05:04.460
The muslin is stiff and makes you look too dressed up, but the organdy seems as if it grew on you.

05:05.640 --> 05:07.700
Anne sighed and yielded.

05:08.160 --> 05:17.140
Diana was beginning to have a reputation for notable taste in dressing, and her advice on such subjects was much sought after.

05:18.000 --> 05:24.720
She was looking very pretty herself on this particular night in a dress of the lovely wild rose pink,

05:25.180 --> 05:33.440
from which Anne was forever debarred, but she was not to take any part in the concert, so her appearance was of minor importance.

05:34.020 --> 05:44.720
All her pains were bestowed upon Anne, who, she vowed, must, for the credit of Avonlea, be dressed and combed and adorned to the Queen's taste.

05:46.000 --> 05:47.600
Pull out that frill a little more.

05:47.940 --> 05:50.700
So, here, let me tie your sash.

05:51.160 --> 05:52.280
Now for your slippers.

05:52.840 --> 05:58.080
I'm going to braid your hair in two thick braids, and tie them halfway up with big white bows.

05:58.660 --> 06:01.480
No, don't pull out a single curl over your forehead.

06:01.940 --> 06:03.380
Just have the soft part.

06:04.200 --> 06:11.440
There is no way you'd do your hair suits you so well, Anne, and Mrs. Allen says you look like a Madonna when you part it so.

06:12.320 --> 06:15.820
I shall fasten this little white house rose just behind your ear.

06:16.340 --> 06:19.420
There was just one on my bush, and I saved it for you.

06:20.560 --> 06:22.680
Shall I put my pearl beads on?

06:22.880 --> 06:23.520
asked Anne.

06:24.120 --> 06:29.260
Matthew brought me a string from town last week, and I know he'd like to see them on me.

06:30.160 --> 06:42.560
Diana pursed up her lips, put her black head on one side critically, and finally pronounced in favor of the beads, which were thereupon tied around Anne's slim, milk-white throat.

06:43.400 --> 06:49.640
There's something so stylish about you, Anne, said Diana, with unenvious admiration.

06:50.340 --> 06:52.420
You hold your head with such an air.

06:53.060 --> 06:54.700
I suppose it's your figure.

06:55.060 --> 06:56.400
I am just a dumpling.

06:57.020 --> 06:59.780
I've always been afraid of it, and now I know it is so.

07:00.700 --> 07:04.380
Well, I suppose I shall just have to resign myself to it.

07:05.080 --> 07:12.260
But you have such dimples, said Anne, smiling affectionately into the pretty vivacious face so near her own.

07:12.840 --> 07:15.480
Lovely dimples, like little dents and cream.

07:16.020 --> 07:18.160
I have given up all hope of dimples.

07:18.660 --> 07:20.740
My dimple dream will never come true.

07:20.740 --> 07:24.220
But so many of my dreams have that I mustn't complain.

07:24.960 --> 07:26.440
Am I all ready now?

07:27.200 --> 07:38.600
All ready, assured Diana, as Marilla appeared in the doorway, a gaunt figure with grayer hair than of your, and no fewer angles, but with a much softer face.

07:39.560 --> 07:42.340
Come right in and look at our elocutionist, Marilla.

07:42.880 --> 07:44.120
Doesn't she look lovely?

07:45.020 --> 07:48.920
Marilla emitted a sound between a sniff and a grunt.

07:49.500 --> 07:51.300
She looks neat and proper.

07:51.680 --> 07:53.720
I like that way of fixing her hair.

07:54.240 --> 07:58.600
But I expect she'll ruin that dress driving over there in the dust and do with it.

07:58.940 --> 08:01.920
And it looks most too thin for these damp nights.

08:02.580 --> 08:08.380
Organdy's the most unserviceable stuff in the world anyhow, and I told Matthew so when he got it.

08:08.620 --> 08:11.560
But there is no use in saying anything to Matthew nowadays.

08:12.140 --> 08:20.860
Time was when he would take my advice, but now he just buys things for Anne regardless, and the clerks at Carmody know they can palm anything off on him.

08:21.380 --> 08:26.880
Just let them tell him a thing is pretty and fashionable, and Matthew plunks his money down for it.

08:27.400 --> 08:31.600
Mind you, keep your skirt clear of the wheel, Anne, and put your warm jacket on.

08:32.500 --> 08:41.420
Then Marilla stalked downstairs, thinking proudly how sweet Anne looked with that one moonbeam from the forehead to the crown,

08:42.000 --> 08:46.840
and regretting that she could not go to the concert herself to hear her girl recite.

08:47.860 --> 08:51.940
I wonder if it is too damp for my dress, said Anne anxiously.

08:52.520 --> 08:56.100
Not a bit of it, said Diana, pulling up the window blind.

08:56.560 --> 08:59.380
It's a perfect night, and there won't be any dew.

08:59.900 --> 09:00.860
Look at the moonlight.

09:01.700 --> 09:07.520
I'm so glad my window looks east into the sun rising, said Anne going over to Diana.

09:08.280 --> 09:15.380
It's so splendid to see the morning coming up over those long hills and glowing through those sharp fur tops.

09:15.800 --> 09:22.620
It's new every morning, and I feel as if I washed my very soul in that bath of earliest sunshine.

09:23.800 --> 09:27.420
Oh, Diana, I love this little room so dearly.

09:27.420 --> 09:31.340
I don't know how I'll get along without it when I go to town next month.

09:32.480 --> 09:35.700
Don't speak of your going away tonight, begged Diana.

09:36.300 --> 09:38.860
I don't want to think of it. It makes me so miserable.

09:39.440 --> 09:41.620
And I do want to have a good time this evening.

09:42.280 --> 09:44.940
What are you going to recite, Anne? And are you nervous?

09:46.000 --> 09:50.040
Not a bit. I've recited so often in public I don't mind at all now.

09:50.560 --> 09:53.000
I've decided to give the maidens vow.

09:53.560 --> 09:54.960
It's so pathetic.

09:55.600 --> 10:01.480
Lara Spencer's going to give a comic recitation, but I'd rather make people cry than laugh.

10:02.420 --> 10:04.440
Will you recite if they encore you?

10:05.080 --> 10:11.400
They won't dream of encoring me, scoffed Anne, who is not without her own secret hopes that they would,

10:11.880 --> 10:16.720
and already visioned herself telling Matthew all about it at the next morning's breakfast table.

10:17.700 --> 10:20.980
There are Billy and Jane now. I hear the wheels. Come on.

10:22.180 --> 10:28.400
Billy Andrews insisted that Anne should ride on the front seat with him, so she unwillingly climbed up.

10:28.960 --> 10:35.060
She would have much preferred to sit back with the girls, or she could have laughed and chattered to her heart's content.

10:35.860 --> 10:38.780
There is not much of either laughter or chatter in Billy.

10:39.440 --> 10:47.580
He was a big, fat, stolid youth of twenty, with a round, expressionless face and a painful lack of conversational gifts.

10:48.140 --> 10:57.520
But he admired Anne immensely, and was puffed up with pride over the prospect of driving to White Sands with that slim, upright figure beside him.

10:57.960 --> 11:04.840
Anne, by dint of talking over her shoulder to the girls, and occasionally passing a sop of civility to Billy,

11:05.360 --> 11:12.840
who grinned and chuckled and never could think of any reply until it was too late, contrived to enjoy the drive in spite of all.

11:13.340 --> 11:23.880
It was a night for enjoyment. The road was full of buggies, all bound for the hotel, and laughter, silver clear, echoed and re-echoed along it.

11:24.260 --> 11:28.300
When they reached the hotel, it was a blaze of light from top to bottom.

11:29.120 --> 11:35.340
They were met by the ladies of the concert committee, one of whom took Anne off to the performers dressing room,

11:35.340 --> 11:44.420
which was filled with the members of a Charlottetown symphony club, among whom Anne felt suddenly shy and frightened and contrived.

11:45.180 --> 11:54.680
Her dress, which, in the East Gable, had seemed so dainty and pretty, now seemed simple and plain, too simple and plain, she thought,

11:55.200 --> 11:59.320
among all the silks and laces that glistened and rustled around her.

11:59.830 --> 12:04.620
What were her pearl beads compared to the diamonds of the big, handsome lady near her?

12:05.160 --> 12:11.760
And how poor her one wee white rose must look beside all the hothouse flowers the others wore!

12:12.780 --> 12:21.440
Anne laid her hat and jacket away and shrank miserably into a corner. She wished herself back in the white room at Green Gables.

12:22.400 --> 12:28.720
It was still worse on the platform of the big concert hall of the hotel, where she presently found herself.

12:29.240 --> 12:34.620
The electric lights dazzled her eyes. The perfume and home bewildered her.

12:35.320 --> 12:42.540
She wished she were sitting down in the audience with Diana and Jane, who seemed to be having a splendid time away at the back.

12:43.160 --> 12:50.780
She was wedged in between a stout lady in pink silk and a tall, scornful-looking girl in a white lace dress.

12:51.280 --> 12:57.360
The stout lady occasionally turned her head squarely around and surveyed Anne through her eyeglasses,

12:57.800 --> 13:03.940
until Anne, acutely sensitive of being so scrutinized, felt that she must scream aloud.

13:04.540 --> 13:13.640
And the white lace girl kept talking audibly to her next-door neighbor about the country bumpkins and rustic bells in the audience,

13:14.560 --> 13:19.980
languidly anticipating such fun from the displays of local talent on the program.

13:20.620 --> 13:25.700
Anne believed that she would hate that white lace girl to the end of life.

13:26.360 --> 13:33.300
Unfortunately for Anne, a professional elocutionist was staying at the hotel and had consented to recite.

13:34.040 --> 13:44.960
She was a lithe, dark-eyed woman in a wonderful gown of shimmering gray stuff like woven moonbeams with gems on her neck and in her dark hair.

13:45.580 --> 13:49.780
She had a marvelously flexible voice and wonderful power of expression.

13:50.540 --> 13:52.980
The audience went wild over her selection.

13:54.260 --> 14:00.800
Anne, forgetting all about herself and her troubles for the time, listened with rapt and shining eyes.

14:01.180 --> 14:05.540
But when the recitation ended, she suddenly put her hands over her face.

14:06.080 --> 14:09.080
She could never get up and recite after that, never!

14:09.680 --> 14:11.340
Had she ever thought she could recite?

14:11.980 --> 14:14.600
Oh, if she were only back at Green Gables!

14:15.360 --> 14:18.740
At this un-propitious moment, her name was called.

14:19.620 --> 14:26.420
Somehow Anne, who did not notice the rather guilty little start of surprise the white lace girl gave

14:26.420 --> 14:31.180
and would not have understood the subtle compliment implied therein if she had,

14:31.540 --> 14:34.980
got on her feet and moved, dizzily, out to the front.

14:35.620 --> 14:43.260
She was so pale that Diana and Jane, down in the audience, clasped each other's hands in nervous sympathy.

14:44.780 --> 14:48.520
Anne was the victim of an overwhelming attack of stage fright.

14:49.440 --> 14:54.980
Often as she had recited in public, she had never before faced such an audience as this,

14:55.480 --> 14:58.840
and the sight of it paralyzed her energies completely.

14:59.740 --> 15:04.320
Everything was so strange, so brilliant, so bewildering.

15:04.720 --> 15:13.000
The rows of ladies in evening dress, the critical faces, the whole atmosphere of wealth and culture about her.

15:13.760 --> 15:17.760
Very different was this from the plain benches at the debating club,

15:18.280 --> 15:21.800
filled with the homely, sympathetic faces of friends and neighbors.

15:22.460 --> 15:26.000
These people, she thought, would be merciless critics.

15:26.780 --> 15:33.040
Perhaps, like the white lace girl, they anticipated amusement from her rustic efforts.

15:33.590 --> 15:37.260
She felt hopelessly, helplessly ashamed and miserable.

15:38.080 --> 15:43.560
Her knees trembled, her heart fluttered, a horrible faintness came over her.

15:44.080 --> 15:49.540
Not a word could she utter, and the next moment she would have fled from the platform,

15:50.020 --> 15:56.120
despite the humiliation which, she felt, must ever after be her portion if she did so.

15:56.740 --> 16:02.060
But suddenly, as her dilated, frightened eyes gazed out over the audience,

16:02.370 --> 16:09.760
she saw Gilbert Blythe away at the back of the room, bending forward with a smile on his face,

16:10.220 --> 16:15.260
a smile which seemed to Anne at once triumphant and taunting.

16:16.160 --> 16:18.700
In reality, it was nothing of the kind.

16:19.260 --> 16:23.700
Gilbert was merely smiling with appreciation of the whole affair in general,

16:24.200 --> 16:29.840
and of the effect produced by Anne's slender white form and spiritual face

16:30.180 --> 16:33.020
against a background of palms in particular.

16:34.160 --> 16:38.040
Josie Pye, whom he had driven over, sat beside him,

16:38.440 --> 16:41.420
and her face certainly was both triumphant and taunting.

16:42.140 --> 16:45.960
But Anne did not see Josie. I would not have cared if she had.

16:46.720 --> 16:50.160
She drew a long breath and flung her head up proudly,

16:50.860 --> 16:54.780
courage and determination tingling over her like an electric shock.

16:55.280 --> 16:58.240
She would not fail before Gilbert Blythe.

16:58.840 --> 17:02.500
He should never be able to laugh at her, never, never.

17:03.160 --> 17:07.660
Her fright and nervousness vanished, and she began her recitation,

17:08.120 --> 17:12.720
her clear, sweet voice reaching to the farthest corner of the room,

17:12.980 --> 17:15.020
without a tremor or a break.

17:15.860 --> 17:18.380
Self-possession was fully restored to her,

17:18.720 --> 17:22.160
and in the reaction from that horrible moment of powerlessness,

17:22.780 --> 17:25.640
she recited as she had never done before.

17:26.280 --> 17:30.320
When she finished, there were bursts of honest applause.

17:31.180 --> 17:35.720
Anne, stepping back to her seat, blushing with shyness and delight,

17:36.360 --> 17:42.000
found her hand vigorously clasped and shaken by the stout lady in pink silk.

17:42.920 --> 17:45.880
My dear, you did splendidly, she puffed.

17:46.100 --> 17:49.120
I've been crying like a baby. Actually, I have.

17:49.640 --> 17:52.520
There, they're encoring you. They're bound to have you back.

17:53.120 --> 17:56.300
Oh, I can't go, said Anne confusedly.

17:56.540 --> 17:59.220
But yet I must, or Matthew will be disappointed.

17:59.720 --> 18:01.320
He said they would encore me.

18:02.140 --> 18:06.000
Then don't disappoint Matthew, said the pink lady, laughing.

18:07.220 --> 18:12.000
Smiling, blushing, limpid-eyed, Anne tripped back

18:12.000 --> 18:14.460
and gave a quaint, funny little selection

18:14.460 --> 18:17.520
that captivated her audience still further.

18:18.600 --> 18:21.680
The rest of the evening was quite a little triumph for her.

18:22.680 --> 18:26.000
When the concert was over, the stout pink lady,

18:26.280 --> 18:28.660
who was the wife of an American millionaire,

18:29.200 --> 18:32.200
took her under her wing and introduced her to everybody,

18:32.760 --> 18:34.820
and everybody was very nice to her.

18:35.640 --> 18:38.520
The professional elocutionist, Mrs. Evans,

18:39.000 --> 18:43.160
came and chatted with her, telling her that she had a charming voice

18:43.160 --> 18:45.980
and interpreted her selections beautifully.

18:46.820 --> 18:50.380
Even the white lace girl paid her a languid little compliment.

18:51.020 --> 18:55.380
They had supper in the big, beautifully decorated dining room.

18:55.980 --> 18:58.900
Diana and Jane were invited to partake of this,

18:59.080 --> 19:01.320
also, since they had come with Anne.

19:01.800 --> 19:03.960
But Billy was nowhere to be found,

19:04.380 --> 19:07.940
having decamped in mortal fear of some such invitation.

19:08.880 --> 19:11.600
He was in waiting for them, with the team, however,

19:11.860 --> 19:14.620
when it was all over, and the three girls

19:14.620 --> 19:19.440
came merrily out into the calm, white, moonshine radiance.

19:20.080 --> 19:24.080
Anne breathed deeply and looked into the clear sky

19:24.080 --> 19:26.860
beyond the dark boughs of the firs.

19:27.400 --> 19:32.100
Oh, it was good to be out again in the purity and silence of the night.

19:32.760 --> 19:36.340
How great and still and wonderful everything was,

19:36.720 --> 19:39.380
with the murmur of the sea sounding through it

19:39.380 --> 19:43.080
and the darkling cliffs beyond, like grim giants

19:43.080 --> 19:46.120
guarding enchanted coasts.

19:46.460 --> 19:49.000
Hasn't it been a perfectly splendid time?

19:49.640 --> 19:51.380
sighed Jane as they drove away.

19:51.860 --> 19:54.220
I just wish I was a rich American

19:54.220 --> 19:56.800
and could spend my summer at a hotel

19:56.800 --> 19:59.720
and wear jewels and low-necked dresses

19:59.720 --> 20:03.460
and have ice cream and chicken salad every blessed day.

20:04.120 --> 20:07.460
I'm sure it would be ever so much more fun than teaching school.

20:08.380 --> 20:10.960
Anne, your recitation was simply great,

20:11.300 --> 20:13.820
although I thought at first you were never going to begin.

20:14.380 --> 20:16.700
I think it was better than Mrs. Evans's.

20:17.340 --> 20:19.880
Oh, no, don't say things like that, Jane,

20:20.180 --> 20:23.140
said Anne quickly, because it sounds silly.

20:23.560 --> 20:26.120
It couldn't be better than Mrs. Evans's, you know,

20:26.380 --> 20:29.680
for she is a professional and I am only a schoolgirl

20:29.680 --> 20:31.680
with a little knack of reciting.

20:32.260 --> 20:35.780
I'm quite satisfied if the people just liked mine pretty well.

20:36.840 --> 20:39.860
I have a compliment for you, Anne, said Diana.

20:40.260 --> 20:42.180
At least I think it must be a compliment

20:42.180 --> 20:44.460
because of the tone he said it in.

20:45.020 --> 20:46.380
Part of it was, anyhow.

20:46.900 --> 20:49.740
There was an American sitting behind Jane and me,

20:49.940 --> 20:54.040
such a romantic-looking man with cold black hair and eyes.

20:54.660 --> 20:57.260
Josie Pye says he is a distinguished artist

20:57.260 --> 21:00.100
and that her mother's cousin in Boston is married

21:00.100 --> 21:02.240
to a man that used to go to school with him.

21:03.160 --> 21:05.620
Well, we heard him say, didn't we, Jane?

21:06.220 --> 21:10.640
Who is that girl on the platform with the splendid Titian hair?

21:11.120 --> 21:13.520
She has a face I should like to paint.

21:14.160 --> 21:17.600
There now, Anne, but what does Titian hair mean?

21:18.340 --> 21:22.840
Being interpreted, it means plain red, I guess, laughed Anne.

21:23.380 --> 21:25.240
Titian was a very famous artist

21:25.240 --> 21:27.160
who liked to paint red-haired women.

21:28.340 --> 21:31.800
Did you see all the diamonds those ladies wore, side Jane?

21:32.300 --> 21:33.800
They were simply dazzling.

21:34.340 --> 21:36.400
Wouldn't you just love to be rich, girls?

21:37.020 --> 21:39.900
We are rich, said Anne staunchly.

21:40.440 --> 21:42.960
Why, we have sixteen years to our credit

21:42.960 --> 21:44.440
and we're happy as queens,

21:44.920 --> 21:47.820
and we've all got imaginations, more or less.

21:48.400 --> 21:49.920
Look at that sea, girls.

21:50.380 --> 21:54.560
All silver and shadow and vision of things not seen.

21:55.260 --> 21:58.040
We couldn't enjoy its loveliness any more

21:58.040 --> 22:01.780
if we had millions of dollars and ropes of diamonds.

22:02.360 --> 22:06.180
You wouldn't change into any of those women if you could.

22:06.900 --> 22:09.080
Would you want to be that white-laced girl

22:09.080 --> 22:11.400
and wear a sour look all your life

22:11.400 --> 22:14.340
as if you'd been born turning up your nose at the world?

22:14.860 --> 22:18.120
Or the pink lady, kind and nice as she is,

22:18.420 --> 22:21.640
so stout and short that you'd really know figure at all?

22:21.960 --> 22:26.320
Or even Mrs. Evans, with that sad, sad look in her eyes.

22:26.820 --> 22:29.460
She must have been dreadfully unhappy sometime

22:29.460 --> 22:30.920
to have such a look.

22:31.520 --> 22:34.120
You know you wouldn't, Jane Andrews.

22:34.500 --> 22:38.760
I don't know exactly, said Jane unconvinced.

22:38.760 --> 22:42.240
I think diamonds would comfort a person for a good deal.

22:43.340 --> 22:46.320
Well, I don't want to be anyone but myself

22:46.320 --> 22:50.160
even if I go uncomforted by diamonds all my life,

22:50.500 --> 22:51.280
declared Anne.

22:51.980 --> 22:54.920
I'm quite content to be Anne of Green Gables

22:54.920 --> 22:57.320
with my string of pearl beads.

22:58.080 --> 23:01.320
I know Matthew gave me as much love with them as ever

23:01.320 --> 23:03.880
went into Madame the Pink Lady's jewels.

23:05.100 --> 23:09.280
End of chapter 33, The Hotel Concert

